We also are strongly encouraging students to complete the semester remotely after visiting family or friends outside the Tucson area.
Our primary goal is to minimize the impact of student travel on community spread of COVID-19.
The testing blitz will also include antibody testing. In addition, we have begun antibody testing for students and employees as of today in more locations, including at the Student Union.

Students are being strongly encouraged to schedule an appointment for a test if they plan to leave their student residence and have not received a positive PCR, antigen or antibody test in the past 90 days.

We have communicated with students about 3 steps to take prior to the holidays, including a testing blitz in mid-November. 
Because of anticipated volume, these tests will be conducted by appointment only, rather than with a walk-in option as we have now. This begins on Nov. 6th.
We continue to see encouraging signs: the past 10 days, from October 8 to October 17, we administered 6,867 tests, with 44 positives, a positivity rate of 0.6%.

Next week, the week of Oct 26, flex in-person courses will have the option of beginning their in-person components (less than 50 students), if public health conditions continue to permit. This is still part of phase 2.
This week, we will continue in-person instruction for classes of 30 or fewer students.
